## Plan Summary

**Only one file needs to change:** `src/routes.ts`

### What the current code does
```ts
router.get("/users", (req, res) => {
  res.json(users);  // dumps all 15 users, no pagination
});
```

### What the new handler will do
```ts
router.get("/users", (req, res) => {
  const page       = Math.max(1, parseInt(req.query.page  as string, 10) || 1);
  const limit      = Math.max(1, parseInt(req.query.limit as string, 10) || 10);
  const total      = users.length;
  const totalPages = Math.ceil(total / limit);
  const offset     = (page - 1) * limit;
  const data       = users.slice(offset, offset + limit);

  res.json({ data, pagination: { page, limit, total, totalPages } });
});
```

### Why each test passes
| Test | Result |
|---|---|
| Default (no params) | `page=1, limit=10` → `slice(0,10)` = 10 items, `totalPages=2` ✓ |
| `?page=2&limit=10` | `slice(10,20)` = 5 remaining items ✓ |
| `?limit=5` | `slice(0,5)` = 5 items, `Math.ceil(15/5)=3` pages ✓ |
| `?page=100` | `slice(990,1000)` = `[]`, no error ✓ |

**Key insight for out-of-range pages:** `Array.slice` naturally returns `[]` when the offset exceeds array length — no special-case handling needed. The `GET /users/:id` handler stays completely untouched.

